Influence of Charge Block Length on Conformation and Solution Behavior of Polyampholytes
Winnie H. Shi, Rohan S. Adhikari, Dilipkumar N. Asthagiri, and Amanda B. Marciel*
Cite This: ACS Macro Lett. 2023, 12, 195−200 Read Online
ACCESS Metrics & More Article Recommendations s*ı Supporting Information
ABSTRACT: We investigate the effect of charge block length on polyampholyte chain conformation and phase behavior using small-angle X-ray scattering (SAXS) and implicit-solvent molecular simulations. To this end, we use solid phase peptide synthesis to precision-tailor a series of polyampholytes consisting of L-glutamic acid (E) and L-lysine (K) monomers arranged in alternating blocks from 2 to 16 monomers. We observe that the polyampholytes tend to phase separate as block size increases. With addition of NaCl, phase separated polyampholytes exhibit a salting-in effect dependent on charge block length. Fourier-transform infrared (FTIR) spectroscopy reveals the presence of intramolecular hydrogen bonds that are disrupted upon the addition of NaCl, implicating both electrostatic interactions and hydrogen bonding in the phase behavior. SAXS spectra at no-added salt conditions show minimal dependence of charge block length on the radius of gyration (Rg) for soluble polyampholytes, but local chain stiffening is found to be dependent on charge block length. With increasing NaCl, consistent with electrostatic screening, all polyampholytes expand and behave as neutral or swollen chains in good solvent conditions. Molecular simulations are qualitatively consistent with experiments. Implications for understanding intracellular condensates and material design are noted.
P
olyampholytes are polymers that contain both positively and negatively ionizable groups along their backbone, leading to a wide range of inter- and intrachain interactions. These interactions influence chain conformation and dynamics and may be exploited to tune the rheological response of polyampholyte-based materials for applications including flocculation, water desalination, and biomimetic tissue
engineering.1−10 Total charge fraction and charge asymmetry have been shown to influence chain conformation and properties such as viscosity and conductivity in polyampholyte solutions.4 However, there is limited fundamental understanding of how these properties are influenced by the sequence of the charged monomers. This knowledge is critical to understanding how intrinsically disordered proteins (IDPs) drive intracellular phase separation of biological condensates. Several theoretical descriptions have been developed to investigate the effects of charge sequence on IDP phase behavior and have shown that an increase in charge block length promotes chain collapse and phase separation.11,12 Nonetheless, these predictions have not been tested exper
imentally against model systems where block length may be systematically varied. Here, we systematically test the influence of charge block length on polyampholyte chain conformation and phase behavior using a combination of sequence-precise synthesis, small-angle X-ray scattering (SAXS), and implicit-solvent molecular simulations. We show that local chain conformation and phase behavior are influenced by charge block length and may be tuned by varying salt concentration. This has implications in IDP phase behavior and design of polymapholyte-based materials. Our experimental system consists of a series of charge neutral polyampholytes with 16 L-glutamic acid and 16 L-lysine monomers arranged in block lengths of Np = 1, 2, 4, 8, and 16
