produced using solid-phase peptide synthesis (SPPS; Figure 1). This strategy provides precise control over sequence, molecular weight, and chirality, thus enabling direct investigation of the role of charge block length on IDP, and more generally, polyampholyte solution behavior. In addition, the identical hydrophilic backbone structures and similar side chain chemistry allow for the effects of electrostatic interactions to be directly examined. Detailed synthesis, characterization, and solution preparation protocols of the polypeptide-based polyampholytes are described in the Supporting Information (SI). Polyampholyte phase behavior (Figure 2) was quantified through turbidity measurements of 1 wt % polyampholyte solutions at various NaCl concentrations. At low added salt
conditions, turbidity measurements show that an increase in Np leads to greater phase separation tendency (Figure 2). At high added salt conditions, large Np polyampholytes exhibit a charge block length dependent “salting-in” behavior, where the minimum salt concentration increases as block length increases. This behavior is attributed to screening electrostatic interactions between oppositely charged groups and is comparable to critical salt concentrations observed for phase separated mixtures of homochiral poly(L-lysine) and poly(Lglutamic acid) (Figure S2). Hence, Coulomb attraction of opposite charges, which vary in strength with charge block length, play a role in phase separation. Interestingly, Np = 2 deviates from the trend in phase behavior and exhibits slight turbidity even at low salt concentrations. In addition to electrostatic interactions between charged side chains, polypeptide-based polyampholytes may also interact via inter- and intrachain hydrogen bond formation. At no addedsalt conditions, Fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR) confirmed the presence of hydrogen bonding for all block lengths (except Np = 4), as indicated by the peak at 1624
cm−1 attributed to β-sheet structures (Figure S3). As the block length increases, there is a higher propensity for hydrogen
bond interactions indicated by a red shift of the 1624 cm−1
peak to 1611 cm−1, along with a decrease in magnitude of the
1644 cm−1 peak associated with random coil chain
conformation (Figure S3).13,14 These results are consistent with the phase behavior previously observed for racemic polypeptide-based polyampholytes, where evidence of hydro
gen bond formation was only found for the diblock sequence.15 Similar behavior is also exhibited for homochiral polypeptidebased polyelectrolytes that undergo phase separation, forming solid-like complexes consisting of hydrogen-bonded β-sheet
structures.14,16,17 Thus, these observations indicate that phase behavior is driven by a combination of charge block length dependent electrostatic and hydrogen bond interactions. The dependence of charge block length on polyampholyte phase behavior noted above suggests the importance of
understanding dilute solution chain conformation.18 To investigate chain conformation, we measure scattering intensity curves, I(q), using SAXS at beamline 12-ID-B at the Advanced Photon Source, Argonne National Laboratory. Dilute polyampholyte solutions at 2 wt % were irradiated in 2 mm quartz capillaries at 13 keV at a detector distance of 4 m (q-range =
0.002−0.5 Å−1) for 0.1 s at 25 °C. The two-dimensional data were converted to one-dimensional scattering curves using the SAXSLee package and then background subtracted and
Figure 1. (A) General chemical structure of the polyampholytes and (B) schematic of the polyampholytes with varied charge block lengths. Blue circles represent negatively charged L-glutamic acid residues and orange circles represent positively charged L-lysine residues. From top to bottom, the polyampholytes are arranged from the smallest (Np = 1) to the largest (Np = 16) block length.
Figure 2. Phase behavior of polyampholytes with varied charge block lengths. (A) Turbidity measurements of polyampholyte solutions at pH 7 in added NaCl concentrations of 0, 100, 500, 1000, and 3000 mM. T is the transmittance (SI). (B) Photograph of the solutions corresponding to the turbidity measurements. Lines in (A) are to guide the eye.
