analyzed using in-house Jupyter Notebook scripts (SI). The scattering intensity curves I(q) for Np < 8 at no-added salt solution conditions (Figure 3A) exhibit a high-q scaling
corresponding to I ∼ q−1/ν, where ν is between 0.5 and 0.33, indicative of polymer behavior in theta to poor solvent quality
conditions.19 This observation suggests, in agreement with
some earlier simulation studies,20,21 that intramolecular electrostatic attraction and hydrogen bond interactions are at play in collapsing the polypeptide-based polyampholytes despite a favorable hydration environment for both side chain and backbone chemistry.
To investigate the influence of charge block length on chain size, the radius of gyration Rg was calculated from the forward scattering intensity I(q = 0) by extrapolation from a linear fit of
a Guinier plot (ln(I) vs q2) in the region where qmaxRg < 1.3 (SI). Interestingly, we observe minimal differences in Rg for Np < 8 polyampholytes, suggesting there is very little charge block length dependence on chain size (Figure 3B). We compare this to implicit-solvent molecular simulations, which exhibit qualitative agreement with experimental data. In particular,
the GB/SA model,22,23 which better treats the collective
properties of hydration24 as compared to the ABSINTH25 implicit solvent model, better captures experimentally determined Rg as well. (GB/SA and ABSINTH are briefly explained in the SI.) These observations indicate that differences in phase behavior and hydrogen bond interactions do not influence the global chain size for this set of small charge block length polyampholytes. We hypothesize that the small block length limits intrachain interactions to local
dipoles,15,26 supporting the reduced influence of block length on Rg (a global measure). GB/SA simulations further support that hydrogen bond interactions are restricted to local scales (Figure S9). These results are at variance with results from field theoretic and complementary MD simulations of a bead− spring model that show that polyampholyte coil size decreases
with increasing block length.11 That study examined a larger range of block lengths not easily accessible experimentally, but the models also lack the chemical detail present in experiments and in models such as GB/SA or ABSINTH. Which, if any, of these explains the difference is an important issue and is left for future studies. To investigate the influence of charge block length on local length scales and chain shape the SAXS data was plotted in a
dimensionless Kratky representation (q2Rg2·I(q)/I(0) vs qRg).
Here, we observe peaks at q ∼ 0.19, 0.20, and 0.23 Å−1 corresponding to 16.5, 15.5, and 13.5 Å for Np = 1, 2, and 4, respectively, which are consistent with Rg values calculated from the Guinier analysis (Figure 4). The shape of the curve in a Kratky representation provides qualitative information on the conformation of polymers in solution. Specifically, we observe that all sequences deviate from the Debye form factor for an ideal chain at high q and that the peak positions appear at values qR 3
g > and above 1.1 (Figure 4), both indicative of
polymers in an unfolded globular conformation.27−29 Yet, for Np = 1, there is a slight upturn at qRg ∼ 5, which reveals chain stiffening at local length scales ∼9 Å or about 2−3 amino acid monomers (Figure 4). Neighboring interactions may lead to
