electrostatic repulsion and chain stiffening for the purely Lchiral (EK)16 side chain sterochemistry (Figure S12). These local structural effects may influence polyampholyte chain dynamics and will be a subject for future study. SAXS measurements at no-added salt conditions show that polyampholytes exhibit collapsed chain behavior attributed to electrostatic and hydrogen bond interactions. To further assess the effects of electrostatic interactions, we vary the solution NaCl concentration and measure scattering intensity using SAXS (Figure 5). As salt concentration is increased, the scattering intensity at high-q shows a charge block length dependent scaling behavior that corresponds to a transition from theta to good solvent conditions (Figure S6). This is consistent with the “salting-in” behavior (Figure 2) and previous studies on statistical polyampholyte phase behavior that show a salt induced theta condition below which chains
collapse and phase separate.4,30 The upturn present at low-q may be indicative of inhomogeneous density fluctuations,
however the physical origin remains unknown.17 Dimensionless Kratky representations further show that polyampholytes transition from collapsed to swollen chains through an ideal random coil condition as salt concentration is increased (Figures 5D and S5). Overall, we observe that increasing the block length increases the salt concentration necessary to reach theta condition, thus indicating that polyampholytes exhibit charge block length dependent chain conformation with varying salt concentration. For charge neutral polyampholytes, it is expected that increasing salt concentration will result in an increase in chain size by screening attractive Coulombic interactions. Here, we observe a charge block length dependent increase in Rg with increasing NaCl concentration, where at 3 M NaCl Rg converges to ∼16−17 Å for all sequences (Figure 5B). GB/SA simulations support our experimental observations, showing an increase and convergence of Rg for the all polyampholytes with increasing NaCl concentration (Figure 5C). At 3000 mM NaCl, FTIR shows that all polyampholytes
exhibit a random coil structure with no secondary structure present (Figure S3). We posit that the charge-driven interactions that collapse polyampholyte chain conformation also mediate hydrogen bond interactions. This result is significant because it suggests that salt can be used to tune the stronger shorter range directional interactions as well as the
long-range electrostatic interactions.31,32 Note that the saltinduced tuning of short-range directional physics is outside the scope of a Debye screening description, and this has implications for developing theories/models of polyampholytes. Polyampholytes show charge block length dependent phase behavior and conformation with varying salt conditions, indicating that the local counterion and solvent environment may play a role in dictating chain behavior. To investigate the effect of sequence on the local counterion environment, we performed NaOH and HCl pH titrations. We observe that the Np > 4 polyampholytes exhibit more buffering capacity, suggesting that counterions remain coupled to the chains (Figure S8). This is consistent with previous simulation results that showed an increase in salt ion localization and tendency
for phase separation with increasing charge block length.15 This behavior seems to suggest that the ionization state would
be lower for sequences with large block lengths.33−36 However, simulation studies have shown that the association of oppositely charged weak polyampholytes leads to an increase in ionization due to energetically favorable electrostatic
interactions.37,38 In addition to electrostatic interactions, chain conformation, concentration and type of salt, and chain hydrophobicity have also been shown to affect ionization
state in polyelectrolytes.39 Thus, investigating how these effects influence polyampholyte ionization remains an interesting topic for future study. In summary, charge block length directly affects chain conformation and phase behavior of polyampholyte molecules. For charge block length Np > 4 polyampholytes, in the absence of added salt, electrostatic interactions and hydrogen bonding
Figure 5. Influence of NaCl concentration on polyampholyte conformation. (A) Background subtracted SAXS profiles of all the blocks at pH 7 for 2 wt % in 3000 mM NaCl. (B) The Rg of polyampholytes determined through Guinier analysis at pH 7 for 2 wt % solution in 0, 100, 500, 1000, and 3000 mM added NaCl concentrations. (C) Rg from GB/SA simulations at increasing salt concentrations for all polyampholytes. Lines in (B) and (C) are to guide the eye. (D) Example shape analysis for increasing salt concentrations through dimensionless Kratky plots for (E K )
4 4 4. Solid lines indicate the Debye form factor fits for the Gaussian coil and dashed lines indicate the infinitely thin rod limit.
