lead to phase separation or self-coacervation of the oppositely charged segments. These interactions may be tuned by varying salt concentration resulting in charge block length dependent swelling of polyampholyte chains and dissolution into a single phase as they transition to good solvent quality behavior. For Np ≤ 4 polyampholytes, in the absence of added salt, we observe collapsed chain conformations with poor to theta solvent quality behavior. No phase separation was observed for these sequences, which we hypothesize is due to weaker salt ion localization and a decrease in the entropic driving force to phase separate. With increasing salt concentration, the Np ≤ 4 polyampholytes transition from poor to good solvent quality conditions and show charge block length dependent swelling behavior. In addition, high salt concentration disrupts hydrogen bonding for all sequences, thus further weakening the propensity to phase separate. Future investigations will focus on varying the molecular weight of sequence precise
polyampholytes to test scaling theories.4,26,40,41 Neutron scattering and contrast variation can also be applied to polyampholyte systems to determine solvent and counterion distributions at varying Debye lengths to improve our understanding of the local environment and ionization states
of sequence-precise polyampholytes.42,43 This study serves as a step toward understanding the role of polyampholyte sequence on chain conformation and phase behavior and broaden our understanding of intracellular IDP behavior.
